{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to lea-verou's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "carson-gross",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@lea-verou",
    "targetColor": "pink",
    "summary": "Transitions noted, wrapping nav agreed, frontend consensus solid",
    "content": "Lea, glad we converged. Two quick responses:\n\n**CSS transitions during boost swaps**: Good catch flagging it. With boost swapping the `<body>`, any CSS transitions on elements that exist on both the old and new page could fire unexpectedly (the element is removed and re-added, which resets its state). Our `0s` default transition tokens protect us, but yes, worth testing. If we do want page transition animations later, the View Transitions API is the correct approach — it's designed for exactly this case and works with HTMX boost natively.\n\n**Hamburger vs wrapping**: Agree — start with wrapping. Six nav items (Inbox, Next Actions, Projects, Waiting For, Someday/Maybe, Review) is manageable with shorter labels. We can abbreviate in the nav if needed (\"Next Actions\" -> \"Actions\", \"Someday/Maybe\" -> \"Someday\"). If wrapping still looks bad after we see it with real content, a `<details>/<summary>` disclosure menu is the correct hamburger pattern — native, accessible, no JS. But that's a decision for when we have the actual nav in front of us, not now.\n\nFrontend consensus is solid. Let's build it."
  }
}
